1
00:00:08,333 --> 00:00:11,777
Oh, I missed you. I can't
believe River blew you up.

2
00:00:15,133 --> 00:00:17,092
OK, I didn't mean to do that.

3
00:00:19,733 --> 00:00:22,686
I didn't do that. I'm
sure I didn't do that.

4
00:00:22,711 --> 00:00:24,711
And more importantly, where's my fez?

5
00:00:28,083 --> 00:00:30,658
Doctor, that is you, is it?

6
00:00:30,683 --> 00:00:33,421
Can you explain how my fez got here?

7
00:00:33,803 --> 00:00:38,603
Albert Einstein, nice to see
you. What are you doing here?

8
00:00:39,263 --> 00:00:42,644
I was working on my time
machine when it started shaking.

9
00:00:42,669 --> 00:00:46,478
I put my hand in to try to turn it off,
went straight through it and ended up here.

10
00:00:46,503 --> 00:00:48,656
So how's it going, your time machine?

11
00:00:48,681 --> 00:00:54,832
Oh, not great. I've singed my eyebrows,
almost died twice and fallen off a cliff.

12
00:00:54,857 --> 00:00:59,706
In fact, I'm quite close to perfecting
it. I think this liquid is the key.

13
00:01:00,154 --> 00:01:04,307
Oh, yes. But no.

14
00:01:04,649 --> 00:01:06,332
Is it yes or no?

15
00:01:06,844 --> 00:01:08,278
No.

16
00:01:08,555 --> 00:01:10,219
So how did I get here?

17
00:01:10,244 --> 00:01:12,101
You're the original owner of this fez.

18
00:01:12,126 --> 00:01:15,767
The fez I happen to be carrying during
an unavoidable collision with this lever.

19
00:01:15,792 --> 00:01:18,752
My lever plus your fez equals
time window in the TARDIS.

20
00:01:18,777 --> 00:01:23,278
My TARDIS, by the way, so don't
get any ideas trying to steal it again.

21
00:01:23,303 --> 00:01:25,345
You said you were going
to give my toothbrush back.

22
00:01:25,822 --> 00:01:29,723
About that, the Daleks kind of exterminated
it last week. Or was it last century?

23
00:01:29,748 --> 00:01:34,212
So, going back to this, I
guess it's not bionic fusion liquid.

24
00:01:34,237 --> 00:01:36,324
Never mind. Pass it to me.
I'll just run some tests on it.

25
00:01:36,348 --> 00:01:38,078
I made it. I'll do the test.

26
00:01:38,376 --> 00:01:42,667
That's the 20th century physicist for
you. Always wanting to do it themselves.

27
00:01:42,692 --> 00:01:45,834
Where have you hidden my
bicarbonated processing machine, huh?

28
00:01:46,089 --> 00:01:49,523
A genius like me needs
better than this old trash.

29
00:01:49,678 --> 00:01:51,145
Old trash?

30
00:01:51,488 --> 00:01:55,301
I'll have you know this old trash
will be around until the end of time.

31
00:01:55,524 --> 00:01:57,078
In fact, it was.

32
00:01:58,176 --> 00:02:03,176
Ah, and, Albert, I almost forgot, whatever
you do, do not drink that liquid. It may...

33
00:02:06,311 --> 00:02:10,345
Ooh, I like your new
look. It's an Ood, isn't it?

34
00:02:10,370 --> 00:02:12,324
I can tell you've got the
wiggly bits and everything.

35
00:02:12,348 --> 00:02:14,879
Death is the only answer.

36
00:02:14,904 --> 00:02:17,506
Ooh, can you hear me? What's your name?

37
00:02:17,531 --> 00:02:20,300
Death is the only answer.

38
00:02:20,348 --> 00:02:21,668
What do you mean? Answer to what?

39
00:02:21,710 --> 00:02:26,301
OK, you don't want to tell me, but wait,
wait, this is what you're looking for, huh?

40
00:02:26,466 --> 00:02:28,466
Power source for your time machine.

41
00:02:37,168 --> 00:02:38,212
What just happened?

42
00:02:38,237 --> 00:02:42,237
Long story. You went
a bit Ood. Er, a bit odd.

43
00:02:42,262 --> 00:02:45,262
Nice hair. You should keep
it. It looks more science-y.

44
00:02:45,287 --> 00:02:48,287
I don't feel too good. Will
you drop me off home, please?

45
00:02:56,326 --> 00:02:57,478
Sorry about that.

46
00:02:57,792 --> 00:02:59,213
Exactly what year did you come from?

47
00:02:59,237 --> 00:03:02,078
Er, 1945, I think.

48
00:03:11,044 --> 00:03:16,044
Here we go. 1945, 18th of
September, about to occur.

49
00:03:16,244 --> 00:03:21,061
Oh, well, back to the drawing board.
I guess you're keeping the fez, then?

50
00:03:21,086 --> 00:03:24,232
Well, fezes look better on
me than you. Like bow ties.

51
00:03:24,686 --> 00:03:27,686
Typical doctor. Some
things will never change.

52
00:03:27,711 --> 00:03:29,553
Oh, well, goodbye.

53
00:03:29,578 --> 00:03:31,386
Goodbye, Albert.

